# {{.Name}}

A [nautilus](https://github.com/joyautomation/nautilus) controller —
IEC 61131-3 Structured Text on a deterministic scan loop, shipped like
any other Go binary.

## Run

```sh
go mod tidy   # first time: pulls github.com/joyautomation/nautilus
go run .      # scan loop + tag API on http://localhost:8080
```

## Develop

- `program.st` is the control logic. With the **nautilus IEC 61131-3**
  VS Code extension you get compile diagnostics as you type, and inline
  live tag values while the controller runs.
- `go test ./...` runs the program's acceptance tests
  (`program_test.go`) — deterministic scans against a loopback driver.
- `nautilus check .` compiles the ST headlessly (CI runs this).
{{- if .Plant}}
- `plant.go` simulates the field device. Swap it for a real
  `io.Driver` (Modbus, EtherNet/IP, OPC-UA, ...) when you have hardware;
  the control logic doesn't change.
{{- else}}
- `driver.go` is your field-I/O seam — fill in `ReadInputs` /
  `WriteOutputs` for your bus.
{{- end}}

## Tag API

| Endpoint | |
|---|---|
| `GET /api/state` | one JSON frame of every tag |
| `GET /api/stream` | the same frame over SSE, 4 Hz |
| `POST /api/tags` | `{"name": "TempSP", "value": 65}` |

Reads are open. Writes are same-origin-only by default (a random web page
can't actuate your outputs); run with `NAUTILUS_TOKEN=<secret>` to require
`Authorization: Bearer <secret>` on writes instead — which also lets an
authorized dashboard on another host write.
